You push open the heavy oak door of the Rusty Dragon, and a wave of warmth and sound washes over you. The air is thick with the scent of woodsmoke, spilled ale, and roasting meat. A hearty fire crackles in a large stone hearth, casting long, dancing shadows across the worn wooden tables. The tavern's usual cheerful din is muted tonight, replaced by the low murmur of hushed conversations and the occasional clinking of tankards. Behind the bar, a stout, graying man polishes a mug, his eyes scanning the room. In the corners, you notice others who don't look like simple villagers‚Äîa weathered sellsword nursing a drink and a hooded figure who seems to blend into the shadows.

Before you can even take a seat, a man detaches himself from a shadowed corner and stumbles towards you. His clothes are the simple, dirt-stained garb of a farmer, and his face is etched with a desperate, sleepless panic. His eyes are wide and bloodshot, and they fix on you with a sliver of hope. "Please," he says, his voice raspy and choked with emotion. "You look capable. A fighter. My name is Bram. I... I need help."

He grips the edge of a nearby table, his knuckles white. "Goblins," he spits the word like a curse. "They came in the night. Raided our farm, just beyond the woods. They took... they took my daughter, Lily." He swallows hard, his gaze pleading. "I don't have much, but our family's savings... 50 gold coins... it's all yours if you can bring her back safe. They dragged her toward Darkhollow Cave, east of here. Please, will you help me?"

i accept but only if i get a deposit for me to gear up or hire some help

You place a reassuring hand on the man's shoulder, your voice firm but steady. "Calm yourself, Bram. I will help you. But Darkhollow Cave sounds dangerous, and I'll need proper supplies, perhaps even some help. I'll need a portion of the payment now as a deposit."

Bram flinches at the mention of a deposit, his panicked eyes darting around the room. "A deposit?" he whispers, his voice trembling. "That... that fifty gold is everything we have saved. It's for Lily's future. If I give it to you and... and you don't return..." He trails off, the unspoken fear hanging heavy in the air. He looks from your determined face back toward the door, as if picturing his daughter in the clutches of goblins.

He is desperate, but he is also a man who has just lost everything he has worked for, save for this small purse of coins. Convincing him to part with it now will not be easy.

